<p><strike>Ideal</strike> anchor brand milk. Lieut. Phillips refused it as he said it was comfort funds stuff &amp; they did not want it. Pte. J.G. Ferguson heard him. If it really true that Comfort fund goods are being sold at the Canteen, it is a shame &amp; should be stopped. It is robbery, &amp; no wonder the Canteen pays.</p>
<p>Tuesday March 12. 1918. 1317<br/>A beautiful day.</p>
<p>I was again out on parade this morning. The drill was bayonett fighting. In the afternoon I was blacksmithing.</p>
<p>I received 5 francs from P.J. Regan for making him a souvenir.</p>
<p>I received a copy of the Portland Observer from my Father and The Leader. Nov 24/17 from K. Miller.</p>
<p>Wednesday March 13. 1918. 1318.<br/>A beautiful day, I was again working on the Mess cart.</p>
<p>I made a fridge out of 9 shell case for E. Thomas this evening.</p>
<p>I finished reading "Modern Geography" by Marion L. Newbigin a very interesting book of the home University Library.</p>
